regular sparse grid. c is a controllable parameter that enables us to tune Œ©a such that its cardinality is minimized
whereas the accuracy of the approximation is the same as with Œ©r . It is worth mentioning that ct = n, ‚àÄ1 ‚â§ t ‚â§ d
results in Œ©a = Œ©r . Fig. 1 (bottom) is an example of a 2d truncated sparse grid. In this case, c = (5, 3) reduces the
number of points from 129 to 89. A 2d full grid with the same reÔ¨Ånement level contains 961 points. The approximation
of our generic function f can be built on top of any of these grids. Without loss of generality, let us consider that our
discretization is realized through truncated sparse grids. The approximation fa : Œ©a ‚Üí R is
