At this point we can introduce the main operations of the sparse grid technique. The init operation initializes the
grid with the values of the function that we want to approximate. Computing the Œ± coeÔ¨Écients of the approximation
is called hierarchization. Using the Œ± coeÔ¨Écients we determine the value of the approximation at any point inside the
[0, 1]d domain. We call this operation evaluation of the sparse grid at a given point.
Data Structures and Algorithms for Sparse Grids
A sparse grid is typically stored in memory as a set of (point, value) pairs. This increases drastically the memory
consumption as for each point O(d) values need to be stored. Our goal is to use a bijection based data structure with
minimal memory consumption, in which only the data associated with the grid‚Äôs points is stored in a 1d array. In other
words, we want to deÔ¨Åne a mapping that takes a multi-dimensional point and maps it to a certain index in the array.
To achieve this we decompose a truncated sparse grid into simple structures which are easy to linearize. Fig. 2 shows
how this is done for the 2d truncated sparse grid from Fig. 1 (bottom). Note that in the rest of the paper we count the
levels starting from 0 instead of 1, i.e. l ‚àà {0, . . . , n ‚àí 1}d and |l|1 ‚â§ n ‚àí 1. n and c remain unchanged.
At the base of our structure, we have the block which contains all grid points that share the same l. Consequently
l is used as identiÔ¨Åer for a block. With our changed notation block l has 2|l|1 points and can be seen as a simple
multi-dimensional array, i.e. b[2l1 ] . . . [2ld ]. On the second level, we deÔ¨Åne group j as the set of blocks l with |l|1 = j,
and introduce a strong order on the set‚Äôs elements. Finally, we store the groups j, 0 ‚â§ j < n in ascending order with
respect to their identiÔ¨Åer j. Based on this layout, we can compute a unique array index of a grid point (l, i) via agp2idx
(its inverse being idx2agp), a mapping deÔ¨Åned by the sum of the following three indices:
‚Ä¢ idx1 is the number of points in groups whose identiÔ¨Åer is smaller than |l|1 .
‚Ä¢ idx2 is the number of points whose identiÔ¨Åer is smaller than l according to the assumed strong order.
‚Ä¢ idx3 is the index of the grid point identiÔ¨Åed by i within its containing block l.
In the following we will see what is needed to compute agp2idx eÔ¨Éciently. Consider the group of blocks l with
|l|1 = j and lt < ct , ‚àÄt ‚àà {1, ..., d}. Let a(d, j) be the number of blocks in group j, so the total number of grid points
within j is a(d, j) ¬∑ 2 j . In order to determine idx1 we then have to count all points in groups with identiÔ¨Åers smaller
that |l|1 , which leads to the following formula
